<section xml:id="app_power_log">
<title>Powers and Logarithms</title>

<subsection xml:id="sec_powers">
  <title>Powers</title>

<p>
In the following, <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> are arbitrary real numbers,
<m>q</m> is an arbitrary constant that is strictly bigger
than zero and <m>e</m> is 2.7182818284, to ten decimal places.
<ul>
<li>
     <m>e^0=1,\quad q^0=1</m>
</li>
<li>
         <m>
          e^{x+y}=e^xe^y,
          \quad e^{x-y}=\frac{e^x}{e^y},
          \quad q^{x+y}=q^xq^y,
          \quad q^{x-y}=\frac{q^x}{q^y}</m>
</li>
<li>
   <m>e^{-x}=\frac{1}{e^x},
   \quad q^{-x}=\frac{1}{q^x}</m>
</li>
<li>
    <m>\big(e^x\big)^y=e^{xy},
    \quad \big(q^x\big)^y=q^{xy}</m>
</li>
<li>
    <m>\diff{}{x}e^x=e^x,
    \quad \diff{}{x}e^{g(x)}=g'(x)e^{g(x)},
    \quad \diff{}{x}q^x=(\ln q)\ q^x</m>
</li>
<li>
    <m>\int e^x\ \dee{x}=e^x+C,
    \quad \int e^{ax}\ \dee{x}=\frac{1}{a}e^{ax}+C</m> if <m>a\ne 0</m>
</li>
<li>
     <m>e^x =\sum\limits_{n=0}^\infty\frac{x^n}{n!}</m>
</li>
<li><p>
    <m>\lim\limits_{x\rightarrow\infty}e^x=\infty,
    \quad \lim\limits_{x\rightarrow-\infty}e^x=0</m>
  </p><p>
    <m>\lim\limits_{x\rightarrow\infty}q^x=\infty,
    \quad \lim\limits_{x\rightarrow-\infty}q^x=0</m> if <m>q \gt 1</m>
  </p><p>
    <m>\lim\limits_{x\rightarrow\infty}q^x=0,
    \quad \lim\limits_{x\rightarrow-\infty}q^x=\infty</m> if <m>0 \lt q \lt 1</m>
  </p>
</li>
<li><p>  The graph of <m>2^x</m> is given below. The graph of  <m>q^x</m>,
for any <m>q \gt 1</m>, is similar.
</p>
<sidebyside width="75%">
  <image source="figs/expGraph2"/>
</sidebyside>
</li>
</ul>
</p>

</subsection>

<subsection xml:id="sec_logs">
  <title>Logarithms</title>


<p>In the following, <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> are arbitrary real numbers that
are strictly bigger than 0 (except where otherwise specified),
<m>p</m> and <m>q</m> are arbitrary constants that are strictly bigger
than one, and <m>e</m> is 2.7182818284, to ten decimal places.
The notation <m>\ln x</m> means <m>\log_e x</m>. Some people use <m>\log x</m>
to mean <m>\log_{10} x</m>, others use it to mean <m>\log_e x</m> and still
others use it to mean <m>\log_2 x</m>.
</p>

<p><ul>
<li>
       <m>e^{\ln x}=x,\quad q^{\log_q x}=x</m>
</li>
<li>
       <m>\ln \big(e^x\big)=x,\quad \log_q \big(q^x\big)=x\quad</m> for all <m>-\infty \lt x \lt \infty</m>
</li>
<li>
        <m>\log_q x=\frac{\ln x}{\ln q},
        \quad \ln x=\frac{\log_p x}{\log_p e},
        \quad \log_q x=\frac{\log_p x}{\log_p q}</m>
</li>
<li><p>
          <m>\ln 1=0,\quad \ln e=1</m>
    </p><p>
          <m>\log_q 1=0,\quad \log_q q=1</m>
    </p>
</li>
<li>
      <m>\ln(xy)=\ln x+\ln y,
      \quad \log_q(xy)=\log_q x+\log_q y</m>
</li>
<li>
     <m>\ln\big(\frac{x}{y}\big)=\ln x-\ln y,
     \quad \log_q\big(\frac{x}{y}\big)=\log_q x-\log_q y</m>
</li>
<li>
     <m>\ln\big(\frac{1}{y}\big)=-\ln y,
     \quad \log_q\big(\frac{1}{y}\big)=-\log_q y</m>
</li>
<li>
     <m>\ln(x^y)=y\ln x,
     \quad \log_q(x^y)=y\log_q x</m>
</li>
<li>
    <m>\diff{}{x}\ln x = \frac{1}{x},
    \quad \diff{}{x}\log_q x = \frac{1}{x\ln q}</m>
</li>
<li>
    <m>\int \ln x\ \dee{x}= x\ln x-x +C,
    \quad \int \log_q x\ \dee{x}= x\log_q x-\frac{x}{\ln q} +C</m>
</li>
<li><p>
    <m>\lim\limits_{x\rightarrow\infty}\ln x=\infty,
    \quad \lim\limits_{x\rightarrow0}\ln x=-\infty</m>
         </p><p>
    <m>\lim\limits_{x\rightarrow\infty}\log_q x=\infty,
    \quad \lim\limits_{x\rightarrow0}\log_q x=-\infty</m>
         </p>
</li>
<li><p>
  The graph of <m>\log_{10} x</m> is given below. The graph of  <m>\log_q x</m>,
for any <m>q \gt 1</m>, is similar.
</p>

<sidebyside width="75%">
  <image source="figs/logGraph10"/>
</sidebyside>
</li>
</ul>

</p>
</subsection>
